@NODE "USAGE" "How to make Slots work and configuration"
@NEXT "REGISTERING"
@PREV "DISCLAIMER"
@TOC "MAIN"

Usage:

        slots "name" <Ansi> <path> <baud> [option]

        Where <Ansi> is either a '1' or 'on' for Ansi capable.
    The <path> is where the SLOTS executable and its files are
    located.  Be sure to end the path with a : or / as needed.
    <baud> is the user's baud rate.  Due to high use of ANSI,
    9600 or better is required.  This can be overridden by putting
    a constant number in its place (ie. 9600)
    [option] is an optional argument to increase compatibility
    with other and future BBS software, you simply replace
    [option] with the text string that your BBS software sends
    saying that ANSI/Extended IBM character set is on.
        For Example:

    If your program doesn't send a '1' or 'on' but a 'Ansi On'
    then use:

        slots "<name>" <Ansi> doors:slots/ <Baud> "Ansi On"

Configuration:

    This only works for the REGISTERED version.  You can configure
    Slots by simply creating a file called "slots.config" in the
    same path as where the rest of the files are stored.

    Inside the file, you simply need three numbers seperated by
    spaces.  They are (in order): days_delay, win_amount, start_turns.

    days_delay  is the number of days a player must wait before getting
                another loan after he/she loses all of their money.
                (default = 1, next day)
    win_amount  is the amount of money needed to win the game.
                (default = 500)
    start_turns is the number of turns given per day.
                (default = 20)

Other stuff:

    Slots also creates a text file called "slots.banner" which is simply
    a text file that shows who the current winner of the game is, so you
    can display this text file if you wanted to during the login sequence.

